### What are Standalone Components?

Introduced in Angular 14, standalone components do not require an NgModule. They manage their own dependencies via the `imports` array. Starting from Angular 15, standalone APIs are stable and recommended for new projects.

### Creating a Standalone Component

```typescript
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { CommonModule } from '@angular/common';
import { RouterModule } from '@angular/router';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-user-card',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [CommonModule, RouterModule],
  template: `
    <div class="card">
      <h2>{{ user.name }}</h2>
      <a [routerLink]="['/users', user.id]">View</a>
    </div>
  `
})
export class UserCardComponent {
  @Input() user: User;
}
```

### Bootstrapping a Standalone App

```typescript
// main.ts
import { bootstrapApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { AppComponent } from './app/app.component';

bootstrapApplication(AppComponent, {
  providers: [
    provideHttpClient(),
    provideRouter(routes)
  ]
});
```

### Routing with Standalone Components

```typescript
// app.config.ts
import { ApplicationConfig } from '@angular/core';
import { provideRouter, Routes } from '@angular/router';

const routes: Routes = [
  { path: '', component: HomeComponent },
  { path: 'about', component: AboutComponent }
];

export const appConfig: ApplicationConfig = {
  providers: [provideRouter(routes)]
};

// main.ts
bootstrapApplication(AppComponent, appConfig);
```

### Using Pipes and Directives in Standalone Components

```typescript
@Component({
  standalone: true,
  imports: [
    DatePipe,              // Pipe
    AsyncPipe,             // Pipe
    HighlightDirective,    // Directive
    NgIf, NgFor            // Structural directives
  ],
  template: `
    <p>{{ today | date }}</p>
    <p *ngIf="visible" appHighlight>Highlighted</p>
  `
})
export class MyComponent {}
```

### Migrating from NgModules

**Before (NgModule):**
```typescript
@NgModule({
  declarations: [UserCardComponent],
  imports: [CommonModule, RouterModule],
  exports: [UserCardComponent]
})
export class SharedModule { }
```

**After (Standalone):**
```typescript
@Component({
  standalone: true,
  imports: [CommonModule, RouterModule],
  // declarations and exports are not needed
})
export class UserCardComponent { }
```

### Benefits

- **No NgModule boilerplate** — Less files and less code.
- **Tree-shakable** — Only imported dependencies are bundled.
- **Lazy-loadable directly** — Can use `loadComponent` in routing.
- **Simpler testing** — Less module configuration in TestBed.
- **Future-proof** — Angular team recommends standalone for all new development.

### Mixing Standalone with NgModules

Standalone components can be used inside NgModule-based apps:
```typescript
@NgModule({
  imports: [UserCardComponent]  // Import standalone component
})
export class SharedModule { }
```

